\begin{cases}
x, & \text{ if } x \geq 0 \\
ax, & \text{ otherwise }
\end{cases}

\]  Here \(a\) is a learnable parameter. When called without arguments, nn.PReLU() uses a single
parameter \(a\) across all input channels. If called with nn.PReLU(nChannels) ,
a separate \(a\) is used for each input channel.  Note weight decay should not be used when learning \(a\) for good performance.  Note Channel dim is the 2nd dim of input. When input has dims < 2, then there is
no channel dim and the number of channels = 1.

